LEPTOSPIROSIS - INDIA (GUJARAT): NOT HANTAVIRUS
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: 31 Aug 2006 20:32:07 +0530
From: T Jacob John <vlr_tjjohn@sancharnet.in>
[Professor John has kindly provided this update on the suspected hantavirus
fatal cases in Gujarat, India. Hantaviruses were ruled out and a
laboratory-confirmed diagnosis of leptospirosis has been made. - Mod.TY]

Surat city in Gujarat had heavy rains and floods recently. Following the
floods, several cases of acute pneumonia syndrome were reported, mostly in
adults. Two differential diagnoses were suggested by local physicians and
picked up by the press: pneumonic plague and hantavirus pulmonary syndrome.
As far as I know, the diagnosis of hantavirus disease, as reported in the
media, was only conjecture and not based on laboratory evidence. A 3rd
diagnosis, namely the pulmonary form of leptospirosis, has now been
laboratory confirmed.
As reported in the Hindu, Chennai edition, 26 Aug 2006, the National
Institute of Communicable Diseases in New Delhi had investigated cases in
Surat. According to Dr Sohan Lal, deputy director of NICD, the illness of 8
patients who died during the last 3 days has been serologically confirmed
as leptospirosis. Of the 30 patients still in the hospitals, 17 had also
tested positive for leptospirosis. These results were given out during a
press conference by Gujarat State health secretary Amarjit Singh, in the
presence of Dr Sohan Lal. They reported that "all tests on human and rodent
samples for plague or Hantavirus pulmonary syndrome had been negative."
The pulmonary form of leptospirosis is a haemorrhagic pneumonia resembling
pneumonic plague and hantavirus pulmonary syndrome. This disease entity has
been recognised and confirmed only since 1993 and many physicians are not
yet familiar with it. (1,2)
References:
1. Sehgal SC, Murhekar MV, Sugunan AP. Outbreak of leptospirosis with
pulmonary involvement in North Andaman. Indian J Med Res 1994; 102: 9-12.
2.Zaki SR, Shieh WJ. Leptospirosis associated with outbreak of acute
febrile illness and pulmonary haemorrhage, Nicaragua (letter). Lancet 1996;
347: 535-6.
Regarding the occurrence of Hantavirus infections in India, I can add one
more reference to the one cited in the ProMED-mail report of 26 Aug 2006
(20060826.2422): Chandy S, Mitra S, Satish N, et al. A pilot study to
provide serological evidence of hantavirus infection in human population in
South India. Indian J Med Res 2005; 122: 211-5.
Thottapalayam, the place where the shrew (_Suncus murinus_) that yielded
the very first hantavirus was caught, is just beyond the northern wall of
the Christian Medical College Hospital in Vellore.
--
T Jacob John
Retired Professor of Clinical Virology
Christian Medical College, Vellore, India
<vlr_tjjohn@sancharnet.in>
[ProMED-mail thanks Professor John for the information and for his
comments. The information again illustrates the need for rapid and reliable
laboratory diagnosis in these kinds of situations. - Mod.TY]
